I have thoroughly enjoyed my time at Salishan Apartments.  The grounds and amenities are great and its very pet friendly.  The maintenance staff is quick to respond to requests and the office staff is professional, friendly, and great communicators.  They have navigated this pandemic with grace and understanding...especially since some of the properties amenities had to stay closed for much of 2020.

If you are looking for a place to live that is pet friendly, affordable, has courteous neighbors, and a management/maintenance staff that takes care of you and cares about the property they steward....I recommend Salishan Apartments.</review>

<Text>STOP! THIS is where you‚Äôre next apartment should be. My Wife and I spent months looking at EVERY apartment complex in Folsom, Roseville, Carmichael, Orangevale and Citrus Heights. Salishan Apartments we‚Äôre the ONLY one that had a great mix of amenities, activities, and all for great pricing. The first thing that we enjoyed about the apartments are the grounds themselves. There‚Äôs an extremely nice river walk with a fountain and a little dog park for our dogs. This was top priority for us as we wanted a nice place our dogs could get out and enjoy every day. The next thing we were happy to see was the package room. Any packages you get from Amazon or anywhere else will be stored safely in a locker that only you call have access to via an app. It‚Äôs so cool! I no longer have to worry about packages being left on my doorstep for hours or days at a time for anyone to steal. Salishan also has quite an amazing Gym with all kinds of really nice and clean equipment for working out with. There are 2 pools, a spa, and a fire pit area which are really nice too. The units themselves are quite spacious. And they come with a washer and dryer IN UNIT! Yes! They also come with fire places which is really cool too. They even tell you during the tour through the unit that they have no problem with you wall mounting your tv or putting up shelving, etc and that they won‚Äôt charge you a fee against your deposit when you move out for it‚Ä¶who does that?! That‚Äôs awesome! The patio that you get is really spacious and enough for a table and chairs if you like to sit outside and enjoy yourself or have a meal.

Perhaps my favorite thing about the apartments though is the fact that the apartments don‚Äôt just take your rent each month and let things around the complex fall apart. They are constantly reinvesting money into the upkeep and upgrading of the complex. They‚Äôve quickly taken care of trees that needed to be removed due to storms or damage. But they didn‚Äôt just remove them, they quickly replanted a bunch of new trees throughout the apartments. They‚Äôve also upgraded the mailboxes with some nice new mailboxes. Right now, they are adding in some sidewalks and redoing curbing around the complex. It‚Äôs just super nice to see the place constantly improving. They care about the way the apartments look and it shows.

Finally, I have to mention the awesome staff. Ruth and her team are awesome. Maintenance is constantly going around and checking on things and are quick to respond to requests. They‚Äôre all super nice and a pleasure to speak with. And everyone in the office is super nice and a pleasure to work with as well. They work hard to keep everything running smooth and it shows.

Salishan Apartments is the first apartment complex where it truly feels like a community and a place that is really enjoyable to call home. <text>I lived here for one year and I'm shocked at some of the negative reviews I read. The staff is great and has accomadated every request I made...timely and resolved completely. Ruth is extremely pleasant, approachable, and professional. I've seen her interaction with others and she's always been friendly and considerate. <userid>114939472778287413124<//userid>< user_name>
Jarret Grathwol< /user_name>
<Date>1512482333861< /Date><rating>5<//rating>< review>
Was in a tricky situation when another apartment situation decided it was prudent to lie about the move in cost among other things all the while playing semantic games about availability. Anyway the end of the month was fast approaching. I had a week to get find a place, see it, get approved, all that bollocks.
In came Nikki to save the day and situation. She took an interest in getting me in despite of all the red tape and communication hassles associated with renting in California. She took the time to show me all the available floor plans in person and to actually take me to the units rather than showing an idealized and inaccurate "model" apartment or even worse, pictures. The best part was the fact she answered all my questions and had the place ready.
The overall vibe of Salishan is as good as it gets for someone new to the community. Always a crew of people making sure the grounds look good, no litter about and actual parking spaces near my unit. My last place I had to practically hail a cab to my car it was so far away- not fun after a days work. It was a real team effort to get me in despite typical paperwork issues (on my part) as I am used to a simpler process back East where I am from.
There were a couple minor issues (sticky bedroom lock and slightly clogged bathroom sink). I let Nikki know and the next day Nick and his associate from maintenance fixed the issues and were great conversation. Also, the buildings numbers are not particularly well displayed, but a map is given to new tenants.
I've rented many places coast to coast and Salishan stands out. Everything works and is in optimal condition in the unit. I look forward to the events and warmer weather where I can use the many amenities like Basketball Courts and Tennis. Meanwhile I can use the indoor fitness center and Racquetball court.
My first few nights I slept very well, which is a good sign for those who travel a lot. It's very quiet and tucked away from the main roads with no trains honking at all hours like the first place I almost moved to.< /review>

The gym has two treadmills and two elliptical machines, twice the treadmills stopped while I was at a fast pace damn near hyperextending my knee as the belt just stopped. They had invested in re-landscaping and used some plants that attract bees, so we have limited the walks with the dog and kids.
After about a month we noticed the stains resurfacing in the carpet, the oven and drier were of deteriorated quality, taking a very long time to heat up and dry. A few months after we moved in, the dog park out front was closed and fenced off. We tried to go to the playground area inside the Salishan grounds, there was dog poop everywhere and the playground was filthy. We returned a couple weeks later to see if it was a fluke but no, just as gross and our basketball rolled over some dog poop and that was the end of that.
They double charged me rent in March, then put a ‚Äòsecond ‚ÄúPay Rent or Quit‚Äù notice‚Äô on my door a few days later (never received the first). After much back and forth I received acknowledgment of their wrongdoing. I felt I was pretty cool about them taking $2400 out of my account (rent is $1200/month), but the front office handled this so poorly it was ridiculous. The following month I reconnected with the manager to verify the autopay was setup and good to go, she never got back to me and I just wrote a check and had my wife take it in. The last time I went to the office with a problem she blew up on me. Perhaps I approached her wrong with my pregnant wife had to jump over the balcony to get into the house because the locks on the front door are shotty.
I‚Äôve determined the owner/managements strategy is to market the place to look like a luxury resort, investing in repaving the parking the lot, landscaping, keeping the front pool clean and pretty (back pool area is a different story). Once your locked in, they don‚Äôt care about you, which explains the high turnover and moving vans every weekend in the parking lot.
The year living here is an experience that needs to be forgotten. The primary reason we moved here was because they took large dogs, Foxborough apartments down the street has the same dog policies, try that place.
When we moved they reported back to potential landlords that I had bounced checks twice, something that was mentioned in the aforementioned ‚Äòsecond notice‚Äô after they had charged me twice that month (and autopay had worked fine the previous 6 months).</Review>

< text>
The Jetty is awesome and has a lot of historic information all around it. You might have to go anywhere to Crescent City to figure out why the cement structures are there and shape that way but it's worth the journey. I did not make it to the lighthouse because I do not allow dogs which I wish they told me that when I was out in the parking lot but I may have missed the sign. Didn't want to leave my dogs in the car on a hot day. But it was a awesome Journey walking around the area I come back every single time :-)</text>

< Review>
The walk down the Jerry to the ‚öì Anchor Graveyard was awesome. Got to see lots of wildlife :crabs, pelcians (most I have seen ) a black bird with a long orange beak (I do not know the name) Kill deer(Yes this is what the birds are called) Cranes and Blue Heron. Also, saw Harbor Seals ,squirrels and seagulls.
There's also a park area with picnic tables , beach access, and toilets. Beach area is Sandy and rocky is safe and clean for childern. Toilets are kept clean also.
Would recommend stopping here if your in the area.< /Review>

If I could a negative star, I would.

This was about the worst Place I have ever been to, and I eat out a lot.

As if she was trying to point out what was wrong with our looks.  And believe me, my friend had on a gym outfit on and I was very preppy. You can check my instagram to see what type of person my friend and I are, or would dress like to ear out. ( ig : @cindyxylex )

The host then directed us to what looked like the smallest table in the darkest corner of the restaurant, next to the kitchen and bathroom entrance. Which resulted in a lot of traffic right next to us.

2) A very unprofessional waiter then approaches me. He does not introduce himself, and does not inform us that he will be our waiter. Noo, He just decides it will be ok for him to get  really close to my ears  as if he was about to tell me a secret and only for me to hear him ask if we wanted some water.

He never spoke loud enough for my friend to hear him and insisted on staying right next to my ear. Forcing me to repeat everything he tells me to my friend across the table.

3) The same rude waiter then brings over the bottle of water already opened, and as he serves it to us, he spills the water on the table and on my friend‚Äôs phone, and never apologizes for it nor does he clean it up and simply hastily rushes back to the kitchen. Whose entrance is again right next to our table if you can visualize that.

4) Another waitress then comes and introduces herself and asks if we need any water or drinks to start, which gives me the impression the previous waiter was not assigned to us. My friend and I go ahead and explain our previous encounter with another waiter and so she insists only she will be taking care of us without asking wha he did.

5) The traffic of people leaving from the kitchen to tables and bathroom becomes more and more intense and we decide this was too much for us to handle and ask the host if we can be given another table and as we are explaining our experience, she starts talking to some guy who approached her without asking us to excuse her.

This was a lie because we came and talked to her after  we saw people leaving a table. Otherwise we would have headed back home.

As we angrily leave disappointed by our experience at a place we were so hasty to try, we see a group of people coming in and they ask to have a table. Which clearly means they did not have a reservation. Well guess what? They were ushered to a table which was not the corner table we were ushered to.

We luckily ended up going to El Carmen which proved to us how rude this place was because their employees were a lot more respectful and nice.

Save yourself from a horrible night and wasted money and DO NOT GO HERE.</text>

<Date>1557597514217<//Date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
Really the only deep dish pizza in town, but don't let that make you think it's just "ok." If you've been to Chicago you'll definitely appreciate these pizzas all the same. Layers loaded with toppings, crust is the cornmeal kind that's study yet delicious. The English Ales beers on tap pairs perfectly with everything. We had the roasted beets for an appetizer which I really enjoyed, the goat cheese and walnuts packing tons of flavor. Staff was friendly and pizza came out sooner than I expected. Great place!< /Review>

While taking a day trip to Monterey, we stumbled upon Heirloom Pizza Co. There was a long wait and the restaurant was full but managed to get bar seating. <user_id>111054693074356547125< /user_id><name>Dan Clark<//name>< time>
1583846134909</time>
<rating>4<//rating><Text>Being an Illinois native I tend to distrust anything that touts deep dish pizza "Just like Chicago's"... Well, Heirloom pizza delivers on that.
Being a carnivore I chose standard fare of pepperoni and sausage. Those ingredients are the dead giveaway for a quality pie. The crust was as good, if not better than my favorite, Lou Malinati's back in Illinois. The right amount of sauce (people tend to skimp on the sauce) to meats ratio, crispy crust but tender and fluffy on the inside.
I had to hold back on a 5 star rating because they rushed the baking right at the end, to expedite the order is my guess, so the cheese didn't melt all the way through,  reducing the cheese pull necessary to achieve that fifth star.
I will be back though. It's truly the best pie I've had out on the west coast to date...<//Text>< pictures>

< text>
Compared to Chicago deep dish........ Mehhhh. But if I'm not comparing, it's pretty good.

I got the new original. First bite was satisfying. But way too many onions. I had to pick out most of it. Especially they are big pieces of onions... Now I have onion taste all over my mouth after finishing my meal. The sauce especially tastes like canned tomatoes... The crust is too bready. Wish it was more crunchy. Didn't like how the texture was like a bread. So when it got soggy it was not pleasing.

I still recommend to those who has never tried deep dish just to get an idea of what it is. but if this place has the classic sausage patty, it would have been awesome because the sausage was pretty good.</text>

< text>
Really delicious food. It's very popular and the overall size of the restaurant is small so be prepared to wait a bit to be seated but it is definitely worth the wait. I had the baked wings which were crispy on the outside but moist and perfectly cooked on the inside. I also had a thin crust pizza with custom toppings and it was top notch and very unique, you can't get a pizza quite like this anywhere else in Monterey. The selection of beer was small but all great choices. I will definitely be eating here again.<//text>

<text>I was excited to finally go try this place and was disappointed. Our waitress was lovely and friendly and asked us if it was our first time there, I said"yes!" Knowing that this was our first experience should have alerted her that it is a good idea to do your best to make it positive. So we ordered the broccoli app and the goat cheese/sausage/arugula/butternut squash pizza. She came back after a while and said the timing was off but here was the broccoli. I didn't know what that meant. The broccoli was good. Then about 10 minutes later we get the pizza. It looked burned on the top - like all the cheese was crispy. Now with regular cheese that might be ok, but it was goat cheese and that is supposed to be fresh and warm, not crispy for sure. We started to eat it as we were STARVING. It didn't have much flavor but I was assuming that it was because it was burnt. So when she came to check in and asked how it was I gave her an unenthusiastic "it's good...." hoping she may clue in. Then at the end when she came to pick it up to put in a box I asked: "So it is always this burnt on the top....? seems a little overdone..." She responded that actually that one was overdone as they kept it in the oven to give us time between the broccoli app and pizza. What!? So she knew it was burnt and still served it to us. I then expected her to offer a discount or even to NOT charge me for it, but no I got the full bill and no apology or credit. I won't come back to this place. <Rate>4< /Rate>< review>
Deep dish done right.  Its actually deep dish pizza not just 2 inches of crust with some toppings like alot of other places.  The ingredients were very fresh and flavorful.  The first bite was heaven. Loaded with cheese, sausage and pepperoni with a pizza sauce that was so good. The chunks of tomatoes in the sauce were delicious and juicy and I dont like tomatoes.  It takes about 30 minutes to make one so dont be in a hurry when going there or order ahead.
It's a small place with seating of about 40 maybe. There is also outdoor seating.  It's a cute place with a little bar in the front. The people were friendly and our server was very helpful and explained everything well. I would have probably given 5 stars if they hadn't run out of the wedge salad and if it hadn't been cold in there.  If I wanted to be cold I would have sat outside.<//review>

0x808de425c8ca6b85:0x7cbfdd98dd5c8f81<//gmapID>
<review>Wow. I haven't had deep dish pizza this good since I moved from Chicago 28 years ago! Chicagoans will know there are two styles of deep dish pizza: Uno pizzeria style‚Äîa high-sided pizza crust filled with extra toppings‚Äîand Edwardo's or Giordano's style‚Äîa *stuffed* pizza, with a thin extra crust on top, topped with crushed tomato sauce. The latter is my favorite. Heirloom Pizza Co.'s pizza is a hybrid. It's a high-sided, filled pizza, like at Uno pizzeria. But it's filled more substantially than Uno's, and looks (and tastes!) very much like Edwardo's/Giordano's. I ordered mine with meatballs, onions, bell peppers, and fresh basil (which came as a shredded garnish on top), and it was fantastic! A small pizza has 6 substantial slices, and three were enough to fill me (with no apps or salad). The restaurant itself is comfortable and charming, with about a dozen tables seating 2 to 4, a bar area, and friendly staff. In the dimly lit dining room, you'll feel comfortable in street clothes or in something a bit fancier on a night out. The only improvement would be to accept waiting list requests by phone (currently you can only get on the list via the web site‚Äîno luck for those of us without smartphones). If I'm ever back in Monterey, Heirloom will be at the top of my dining list.< /review>< Rate>

<user_name>Tom Loredo</user_name><date>1553143379285</date>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< Text>
Wow. I haven't had deep dish pizza this good since I moved from Chicago 28 years ago! Chicagoans will know there are two styles of deep dish pizza: Uno pizzeria style‚Äîa high-sided pizza crust filled with extra toppings‚Äîand Edwardo's or Giordano's style‚Äîa *stuffed* pizza, with a thin extra crust on top, topped with crushed tomato sauce. The latter is my favorite. Heirloom Pizza Co.'s pizza is a hybrid. It's a high-sided, filled pizza, like at Uno pizzeria. But it's filled more substantially than Uno's, and looks (and tastes!) very much like Edwardo's/Giordano's. I ordered mine with meatballs, onions, bell peppers, and fresh basil (which came as a shredded garnish on top), and it was fantastic! A small pizza has 6 substantial slices, and three were enough to fill me (with no apps or salad). The restaurant itself is comfortable and charming, with about a dozen tables seating 2 to 4, a bar area, and friendly staff. In the dimly lit dining room, you'll feel comfortable in street clothes or in something a bit fancier on a night out. The only improvement would be to accept waiting list requests by phone (currently you can only get on the list via the web site‚Äîno luck for those of us without smartphones). If I'm ever back in Monterey, Heirloom will be at the top of my dining list.</Text>

<UserId.>117438384361371815487</UserId.><name>Justin Bradley<//name>< date>
1519365753520< /date>
< rate>
2</rate>
<Text>If a hipster could become a restaurant it would be this place, I wish I hadn't wasted my money. I went here with a group of friends with a glowing recommendation from another friend (whose judgment I now question deeply.) I will state the positives first. The pizza was ok, not great but it was good and in a unique kind of way. Visually the restaurant looked appealing, but that was the extent of it. If you are really into clean, organic ingredients, and knowing where they are sourced this place might be for you. If you are not int that, or paying 3x what the meal is worth for that kind of product this place is not for you, it was not for me. So now let me let you in on why this place barely skated by on a 2 star for me. My meal was $45 for a small pizza, a salad and a soda. I was not impressed with my pizza, as there are many places i feel do a great job at a better price. As I said, this place was ok not great. My Cesar salad was ok. The soda (a fair trade soda) was good. My other friends that were with me did not like their pizza enough to even take the left overs home. The service was fine, with the exception of the awkward service provided by what I think was the owner. When we came in this person was seated at the bar watching tv in a dirty mad hatter's shirt and jeans. when he got up and asked us "how many?" we all had the same reaction of awkwardness. he clumsily went and cleaned a table and gestured for us to be seated. Judging by his appearance and that the tv was pulling his attention he did not seem to have much pride in what he was doing. Finally, it was uncomfortable. It was a chilly night, and over head was a massive fan on full tilt inside the restaurant.  It was just as uncomfortable inside as it was outside. The women in our group were really off put by this. I assume the circulation was necessary as the space was small, but it still was not comfortable. This place gets 2 stars because it is unique in its offering, and the servers were friendly. For the quality of food and service I would have expected to pay $15 for my meal, and at that price I might frequent this place. As it stands I wish I had spent my time with my friends in ANY other restaurant in the area.</Text><pictures>None<//pictures>< Resp>

We, my wife, I and my oldest son shared a large pizza. This one was half Napoli and half heritage, with the thin crust. I have to say, these people know how to make pizza's. The pizza was big enough for the three of us. I found the restaurant itself tastefully decorated and there was a pleasant buzz inside. They serve fine wines and tasty specialty beers. The staff were friendly and attentive. I really recommend this restaurant!

<Rating>3<//Rating><gmap_id>0x80c2b43be0dbb991:0x4500547e27e08cfd</gmap_id>< Review>
Small, neighborhood Walmart carrying mostly groceries, liquor, basic household essentials, personal hygiene (body wash/soap, toothpaste/brush, hair care, etc), and a pharmacy.

This is not your typical Walmart and definitely not a Walmart Super Center. It does NOT carry clothing/shoes, furniture, appliances, electronics, sporting goods, outdoor patio items.

Overall - good prices on food/groceries, liquor, and cleaning supplies. However, there is a very limited selection compared to other Walmart Neighborhood Markets and much smaller selection than the Vons located nearby (less than a mile away).< /Review>

107779356723613717368< /UserId.>
< text>
After shopping at the huge, space wasting Walmart department stores I didn't think I'd like this but I was a little wrong. They don't have the most enlightened HR policies so I take that into account when dealing with 'associates'. Now to the Neighborhood Market ....
Unlike some other large chains I've been able to find a few national brand items that I prefer. The dairy and in-store baked bread items are good value. I've also found their house brand OTC pharmacy items are the right quantity and much better price than the other pharmacy across the corner. Heck, they even have hard-to-find, locally made Romeros 10" flour tortillas. I think I noticed ground lamb, very difficult to find locally. Unexpectedly the produce section items are high priced and chosen for appearance than ripeness.
The main downside is that the stores unusual popularity among the downscale set has made parking very difficult, especially for the victim Del Taco next door.< /text>

Mick Freeley< /name>
